arlotte Mew (1869–1928) In Nunhead Cemetery -- tLaurence Binyon (1869–1943) As I Walked Through London -- tT. E. Hulme (1883–1917) The Embankment -- tEzra Pound (1885–1972) -- tD. H. Lawrence (1885–1930) -- tFrances Cornford (1886–1960) -- tSiegfried Sassoon (1886–1967) Monody on the Demolition of Devonshire House -- tT. S. Eliot (1888–1965) -- tIsaac Rosenberg (1890–1918) Fleet Street -- tRichard Aldington (1892–1962) -- tWilfred Owen (1893–1918) “I am the ghost of Shadwell Stair” -- tSylvia Townsend Warner (1893–1978) -- tJohn Rodker (1894–1955) -- tRobert Graves (1895–1985) Armistice Day, 1918 -- tA. S. J. Tessimond (1902–1962) -- tStevie Smith (1902–1971) Suburb -- tWilliam Empson (1906–1984) Homage to the British Museum -- tJohn Betjeman (1906–1984) -- tLouis MacNeice (1907–1963) -- tStephen Spender (1909–1995) -- tBernard Spencer (1909–1963) -- tMervyn Peake (1911–1968) London Buses -- tKenneth Allott (1912–1973) Memento Mori -- tRoy Fuller (1912–1991) -- tAnne Ridler (1912–2001) Wentworth Place: Keats Grove -- tGeorge Barker (1913–1991) Kew Gardens -- tAlun Lewis (1915–1944) Westminster Abbey -- tRobert Lowell (1917–1977) -- tNicholas Moore (1918–1986) Monmouth Street -- tJohn Heath-Stubbs (1918–2006) -- tW. S. Graham (1918–1986) The Night City -- tMuriel Spark (1918–2006) from A Tour of London -- tKeith Douglas (1920–1944) from The “Bête Noire” Fragments -- tD. J. Enright - Ahren Warner (1986–) -- tCredits und Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCalled “the flour of Cities all,” London has long been understood through the poetry it has inspired. Now poet Mark Ford has assembled the most capacious and wide-ranging anthology of poems about London to date, from Chaucer to Wordsworth to the present day, providing a chronological tour of urban life and of English literature. Nearly all of the major poets of British literature have left some poetic record of London: Chaucer, Spenser, Shakespeare, Donne, Milton, Dryden, Pope, Johnson, Wordsworth, Keats, Byron, and T. S. Eliot. Ford goes well beyond these figures, however, to gather significant verse of all kinds, from Jacobean city comedies to nursery rhymes, from topical satire to anonymous ballads. The result is a cultural history of the city in verse, one that represents all classes of London’s population over some seven centuries, mingling the high and low, the elegant and the salacious, the courtly and the street smart. Many of the poems respond to large events in the city’s history—the beheading of Charles I, the Great Fire, the Blitz—but the majority reflect the quieter routines and anxieties of everyday life through the centuries. Ford’s selections are arranged chronologically, thus preserving a sense of the strata of the capital’s history. An introductory essay by the poet explores in detail the cultural, political, and aesthetic significance of the verse inspired by this great city. The result is a volume as rich and vibrant and diverse as London itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aPOETRY / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh1 aFord, Mark, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311066590140uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/9780674273702zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674273702423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674273702/original  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSH